The Chesapeake Modeling Symposium 2012, May 21 - 22, 20, Annapolis, MD (http://www.chesapeakemeetings.com/CheMS2012/):  

Interfacing between modeling, management and the public: TMDLs,  politics, litigation and conflicting stakeholder interests


 The funds received from the NSF were used to lower registration fees for 17 students to encourage attendance at the bi-ennial modeling symposium convened by the Chesapeake Community Modeling Program (http://ches.communitymodeling.org/).  The meeting brings together highly skilled modelers to discuss the technical aspects of their models as well as the application of the models to societal/management needs in the Chesapeake Bay and its watershed.  The meeting, therefore, provides emerging modelers from graduate programs to actively interact with their more experienced colleagues, enabling knowledge transfer, and importantly networking for insuring continued educational and research opportunities for the new cohort of the modeling community.  This meeting particularly had the added benefit for exposure and dialog with the ecosystem restoration and management community, allowing the new modelers to assess their abilities to provide practical applicable models for routine use in improving water quality and the regionÆs aquatic living resources.   Of the 17 students receiving the registration reduction, 5 presented posters and 3 oral presentations.


